ns0:Resource.title: GALEX Release 6

curation.publisher: WFAU, Institute for Astronomy, University of Edinburgh

content.subject: UV
content.description: The Galaxy Evolution Explorer (GALEX) satellite is a NASA mission led by the California Institute of Technology to investigate how star formation in galaxies evolved from the early Universe up to the present. GALEX uses microchannel plate detectors to obtain direct images in the near-UV (NUV) and far-UV (FUV) and a grism to disperse light for low resolution spectroscopy

column.name: obj
column.description: Flux (pho/sec/cm^2/Ang) (standard) Spectrum array in photons per second per cm^2 per Angstrom. This is the standard reduction which means a simple sum of the pixels in the object region (given by (objwidth), see -gsax.fits file) after dividing by the response image and subtracting an average background level at each wavelength point (or column). Only NUV 1st order and FUV 2nd order are used to compute this spectrum.

column.name: objerr
column.description: Error on obj, one sigma error in standard extraction spectrum

column.name: opx
column.description: Flux (pho/sec/cm^2/Ang) (optimal) Optimally-weighted extracted spectrum using a profile model. The profile model is the same for the entire field, so this computation is best for unresolved sources.

column.name: opxerr
column.description: Error on opx, one sigma error in optimal extraction spectrum.x

column.name: objs
column.description: Flux (pho/sec/cm^2/Ang) (FUV 3rd + NUV 2nd) Secondary spectrum-- this is similar to (obj) but only the NUV 2nd order and FUV 3rd order are used to extract the spectrum (instead of only NUV 1st and FUV 2nd). This is expected to have a much lower S/N but will have a higher spectral resolution than (obj).
